-- ── Langfuse ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Langfuse is an open-source LLM engineering platform for tracing, evaluating, and managing prompts in production AI applications, now owned by ClickHouse.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Hobby, self-hosted or cloud); paid plans from $29/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2022, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$11-50 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Berlin, Germany$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Langfuse Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Langfuse is an open-source LLM observability and evaluation platform, now part of ClickHouse. See 2026 pricing, tracing and eval features, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Langfuse is an open-source LLM engineering platform that helps teams trace, evaluate, debug, and collaboratively manage prompts for applications built on large language models. The company was founded in 2022 by Maximilian Deichmann, Marc Klingen, and Clemens Rawert, a Berlin-based founding team that went through Y Combinator's Winter 2023 batch, relocating temporarily to San Francisco for the program before returning to Germany once it concluded; the timing meant the team began building Langfuse just as GPT-4 was initially released, positioning the product early in the emerging LLM observability category. Langfuse raised a $4 million seed round led by Lightspeed Venture Partners with participation from La Famiglia and Y Combinator, bringing total disclosed funding to roughly $4.5 million across two rounds. On January 16, 2026, ClickHouse, the analytical database company, announced it had acquired Langfuse alongside the close of ClickHouse's own $400 million Series D funding round; financial terms of the Langfuse acquisition were not disclosed. At the time of acquisition, Langfuse reported more than 2,000 paying customers, over 26 million SDK installs per month, more than 6 million Docker pulls, and usage by 19 of the Fortune 50 and 63 of the Fortune 500, making it one of the most widely deployed open-source LLM observability platforms. Notably, Langfuse's own architecture already ran entirely on ClickHouse's database technology for both its cloud offering and self-hosted deployments prior to the acquisition, which the companies cited as a key strategic rationale; both companies stated that Langfuse remains one hundred percent open source under its existing MIT license for core features, continues to support production-scale self-hosting, and that Langfuse Cloud continues operating as a standalone service with an unchanged roadmap. Technically, Langfuse follows an open-core model in which the tracing engine, integrations, API, data model, and export functionality are MIT-licensed and free to self-host via Docker, while certain advanced enterprise features are reserved for paid tiers. The platform's core capability is distributed tracing for LLM applications: every trace captures each operation in a request, including individual LLM calls, retrieval steps, tool executions, and custom application logic, along with timing, inputs, outputs, and metadata, giving engineers full visibility into what happened during a given interaction. On top of tracing, Langfuse provides prompt management for centrally versioning, collaboratively editing, and iterating on prompts outside of application code; an evaluation system supporting human feedback, end-user signals, and automated LLM-as-a-judge scoring; datasets and experiments for testing which prompt or model version performs better before shipping changes to production; and an interactive playground for testing prompts directly, with the ability to link playground sessions back to real production traces. The platform integrates with the OpenAI SDK, LangChain, LlamaIndex, LiteLLM, and the broader OpenTelemetry ecosystem, and can run as a fully managed cloud service or a self-hosted Docker deployment a team fully controls. Langfuse's pricing spans four published cloud tiers: Hobby is free and includes 50,000 observability units per month, 30 days of data retention, and up to two users with community support via GitHub; Core costs $29 per month and includes 100,000 units with additional usage billed at $8 per 100,000 units, 90 days of retention, unlimited users, and in-app support; Pro costs $199 per month and includes 100,000 units, three years of data retention, unlimited annotation queues, and SOC2 and ISO27001 compliance reports, with an optional Teams add-on at $300 per month for SSO and role-based access control; and Enterprise costs $2,499 per month on a yearly commitment and adds audit logs, a SCIM API, custom rate limits and SLAs, and a dedicated support engineer, with custom volume pricing available. Usage beyond included allowances is billed on a graduated scale ranging from $8 per 100,000 units at lower volumes down to $6 per 100,000 units above 50 million units per month. Langfuse's core audience is engineering teams building and operating production LLM applications who need visibility into model behavior, cost, and quality at scale, ranging from individual developers using the free Hobby tier to enterprises with Fortune 500-scale deployments. It competes directly with LangSmith (LangChain's own observability platform), Helicone, Arize AI's Phoenix, Weights and Biases Weave, Braintrust, and general-purpose observability vendors like Datadog that have added LLM-specific monitoring; Langfuse differentiates itself primarily through its open-source, self-hostable core under a permissive MIT license, framework-agnostic integrations that do not require adopting LangChain specifically, and, following the ClickHouse acquisition, backing by a well-resourced analytical database company that already powers Langfuse's own infrastructure.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'c392b66f-4dcb-40e6-989c-f072b529aff7';

